#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:8
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"SYNOPSIS:\n"
"\tHow to get your shiny LFS box to shutdown when you press the\n"
"\tpower button.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:11
msgid "HINT:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:16
msgid ""
"ACPI [1] is the advanced Configuration and Power interface.  It basically is "
"an upgrade of the old Advanced Power Management interface, and allows for "
"much more flexibility in configuring actions to certain events."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:19
msgid ""
"The ACPI Daemon is a user space daemon that reacts to these events through "
"the /proc interface."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:22
msgid ""
"To get the package fire this link up in your browser and choose your "
"favourite sourceforge mirror."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:24
msgid "http://prdownloads.sourceforge.net/acpid/acpid-1.0.1.tar.gz?download"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:26
msgid "Or use wget on :"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:28
msgid "http://umn.dl.sourceforge.net/sourceforge/acpid/acpid-1.0.1.tar.gz"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:33
msgid ""
"First of all you need to ensure your motherboard and power supply supports "
"the ACPI standard.  Most models post 2000 should be Ok, as well as a few "
"before that, check your manufacturers documentation though."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:38
msgid ""
"ACPID should be used in conjunction with kernels greater than 2.4.8, but "
"versions before that can be patched with the latest ACPI drivers.  This "
"shouldn't be a concern for LFS people, with linux-2.4.19 as standard."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:50
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Next step is to ensure that your kernel has the drivers loaded, either\n"
"in the kernel proper or as modules. \n"
"[*] Power Management support\n"
"[*]   ACPI support (NEW)\n"
"[ ]     ACPI Debug Statements (NEW)\n"
"<M>     ACPI Bus Manager (NEW)\n"
"<M>       System\n"
"<M>       Processor\n"
"<M>       Button\n"
"< >       AC Adapter\n"
"< >       Embedded Controller              \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:53
msgid "If you're on a laptop you can add in AC Adaptor and Embedded Controller."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:60
msgid ""
"The usual procedures apply for installing your new kernel and modules.  The "
"modules are called: ospm_busmgr ospm_system ospm_processor ospm_button"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:63
msgid ""
"I'm not sure about the AC adaptor and Embedded Controller, because I don't "
"have a laptop to test it on."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:65
msgid "So do something like the following if you are using BSD style init."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:72
msgid ""
"cat >> /etc/rc.d/rc.modules << \"EOF\" modprobe ospm_busmgr modprobe "
"ospm_system modprobe ospm_processor modprobe ospm_button EOF"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:74
msgid "and this for sysvinit.  Thanks to D�nis Volpato Martins"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:78
msgid ""
"cat > $rc_base/init.d/acpid << \"EOF\" #!/bin/bash # Begin "
"$rc_base/init.d/acpid"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:82
msgid ""
"# Based on sysklogd script from LFS-3.1 and earlier.  # Rewritten by D�nis "
"Volpato Martins - dvm@linux-sc.org # based on acpid hint"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:85
msgid "source /etc/sysconfig/rc source $rc_functions"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:93
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"case \"$1\" in\n"
"\tstart)\n"
"\t\techo \"Starting acpid...\"\n"
"\t\tmodprobe ospm_busmgr\n"
"\t\tmodprobe ospm_system\n"
"\t\tmodprobe ospm_processor\n"
"\t\tmodprobe ospm_button\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:96
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\t\tloadproc acpid\n"
"\t\t;;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:101
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tstop)\n"
"\t\techo \"Stopping acpid...\"\n"
"\t\tkillproc acpid\n"
"\t\t;;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:106
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\treload)\n"
"\t\techo \"Reloading acpid...\"\n"
"\t\treloadproc acpid 1\n"
"\t\t;;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:112
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\trestart)\n"
"\t\t$0 stop\n"
"\t\tsleep 1\n"
"\t\t$0 start\n"
"\t\t;;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:116
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tstatus)\n"
"\t\tstatusproc acpid\n"
"\t\t;;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:122
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\t*)\n"
"\t\techo \"Usage: $0 {start|stop|reload|restart|status}\"\n"
"\t\texit 1\n"
"\t\t;;\n"
"esac\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:125
msgid "# End $rc_base/init.d/acpid EOF"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:128
msgid ""
"there is some symlinking to do here, but I'm not sure how that works "
"either. Will research it one day."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:132
msgid ""
"Next, on to the ACPI Daemon.  The source requires no ./configure, as it only "
"depends on the kernel, so do a"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:134
msgid "make && make install"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:136
msgid "as root."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:138
msgid "Now for the configuring."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:141
msgid ""
"We need to make an acpi directory under /etc, and an events directory under "
"that."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:143
msgid "mkdir -p /etc/acpi/events"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:145
msgid "First of all is the event Handler."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:149
msgid ""
"cat > /etc/acpi/acpi_handler.sh << \"EOF\" #!/bin/sh # Default acpi script "
"that takes an entry for all actions"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:151
msgid "set $*"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:166
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"case \"$1\" in\n"
"  button)\n"
"    case \"$2\" in\n"
"   power)  /sbin/init 0\n"
"        ;;\n"
"       *)      logger \"ACPI action $2 is not defined\"\n"
"        ;;\n"
"    esac\n"
"        ;;\n"
"       *)      logger \"ACPI group $1 / action $2 is not defined\"\n"
"        ;;\n"
"esac\n"
"EOF\n"
"chmod 755 /etc/acpi/event_handler.sh\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:169
msgid "next, an events file"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:174
msgid ""
"cat > /etc/acpi/events/default << \"EOF\" # This is the ACPID default "
"configuration, it takes all # events and passes them to /etc/acpi/default.sh "
"for further # processing."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:180
msgid ""
"# event keeps a regular expression matching the event. To get # power events "
"only, just use something like \"event=button power.*\" # to catch it.  # "
"action keeps the command to be executed after an event occurs #This halts "
"the computer when the Power button is pressed."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:183
msgid "event=button power.* action=/sbin/shutdown -h now"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:187
msgid ""
"# Optionally you can specify the placeholder %e. It will pass # through the "
"whole kernel event message to the program you've # specified."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:192
msgid ""
"event=.* action=/etc/acpi/acpi_handler.sh %e EOF chmod 755 "
"/etc/acpi/events/default"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:195
msgid "you can add actions for other events."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:198
msgid "And now you can run, as root # acpid"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:201
msgid ""
"To get acpid to run on boot, add /usr/sbin/acpid into your rc.local file. Or "
"use the above rc.acpid for sysvinit."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/acpid.txt:205
msgid ""
"Test if it works by pressing your power button.  I've never experienced any "
"problems with doing this. But email me if you get into trouble."
msgstr ""

